WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:01.782
Welcome back!

00:00:01.782 --> 00:00:04.519
Last time you saw the fork commands.

00:00:04.519 --> 00:00:07.256
Now let's watch what they actually mean:

00:00:07.256 --> 00:00:08.820
a live database app,

00:00:08.820 --> 00:00:09.993
copied in seconds,

00:00:09.993 --> 00:00:10.776
edited freely,

00:00:10.776 --> 00:00:13.513
while the original never notices a thing.

00:00:14.292 --> 00:00:15.626
Here's the setup:

00:00:15.626 --> 00:00:18.295
a real PostgreSQL with a pgAdmin

00:00:18.295 --> 00:00:19.630
interface on top,

00:00:19.630 --> 00:00:21.409
live on the server.

00:00:21.409 --> 00:00:24.078
A fork is an instant copy-on-write

00:00:24.078 --> 00:00:26.302
twin of all of it.

00:00:26.302 --> 00:00:28.082
Same data at birth,

00:00:28.082 --> 00:00:29.861
completely separate lives after.

00:00:33.126 --> 00:00:34.778
Meet the app:

00:00:34.778 --> 00:00:35.328
demo-pgadmin,

00:00:35.328 --> 00:00:38.081
a PostgreSQL with a pgAdmin

00:00:38.081 --> 00:00:38.632
interface,

00:00:38.632 --> 00:00:40.284
mounted and running.

00:00:43.284 --> 00:00:44.224
One live repo.

00:00:44.224 --> 00:00:45.164
Let's clone it.

00:00:45.673 --> 00:00:47.136
This is the original,

00:00:47.136 --> 00:00:48.233
in the browser.

00:00:48.233 --> 00:00:50.062
pgAdmin asks for a login,

00:00:50.062 --> 00:00:51.890
because it's the production copy,

00:00:51.890 --> 00:00:53.353
and production stays guarded.

00:00:53.353 --> 00:00:54.450
Once we're in,

00:00:54.450 --> 00:00:57.010
let's open the query tool and look

00:00:57.010 --> 00:00:58.107
at the data:

00:00:58.107 --> 00:01:00.667
a tasks table with four real rows.

00:01:19.340 --> 00:01:20.161
Fork it.

00:01:20.161 --> 00:01:23.035
The copy-on-write clone takes seconds regardless of

00:01:23.035 --> 00:01:23.446
size;

00:01:23.446 --> 00:01:26.321
detach returns as soon as the containers

00:01:26.321 --> 00:01:26.731
start,

00:01:26.731 --> 00:01:29.606
while health checks continue in the background.

00:01:29.708 --> 00:01:30.635
Forked and starting.

00:01:30.635 --> 00:01:33.417
The data did not get copied — it got

00:01:33.417 --> 00:01:33.726
shared,

00:01:33.726 --> 00:01:35.272
until one side changes it.

00:01:38.522 --> 00:01:40.537
And here's the fork's pgAdmin.

00:01:40.537 --> 00:01:42.149
No login this time:

00:01:42.149 --> 00:01:43.761
forks are disposable sandboxes,

00:01:43.761 --> 00:01:45.776
so the gate steps aside.

00:01:45.776 --> 00:01:47.388
Run the same query,

00:01:47.388 --> 00:01:49.000
and there they are,

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:50.613
the same four tasks.

00:01:50.613 --> 00:01:52.628
The fork inherited every row.

00:02:30.388 --> 00:02:31.509
Two repositories now:

00:02:31.509 --> 00:02:33.376
the original and the experiment,

00:02:33.376 --> 00:02:35.242
each with its own containers,

00:02:35.242 --> 00:02:35.616
network,

00:02:35.616 --> 00:02:36.736
and disk view.

00:02:39.736 --> 00:02:41.032
Same machine,

00:02:41.032 --> 00:02:42.975
two isolated worlds.

00:02:46.288 --> 00:02:47.245
Done experimenting?

00:02:47.245 --> 00:02:48.681
Delete the fork.

00:02:48.681 --> 00:02:50.116
Seconds to create,

00:02:50.116 --> 00:02:52.987
seconds to throw away — the

00:02:52.987 --> 00:02:55.379
original never knew it existed.

00:02:58.379 --> 00:02:58.725
Gone.

00:02:58.725 --> 00:03:01.148
The original kept serving the whole time.

00:03:01.951 --> 00:03:03.166
So fork freely,

00:03:03.166 --> 00:03:04.786
production can't get hurt.

00:03:04.786 --> 00:03:05.595
Next up,

00:03:05.595 --> 00:03:07.215
we look at secrets,

00:03:07.215 --> 00:03:10.049
the one thing your forks deliberately don't

00:03:10.049 --> 00:03:10.454
inherit.

00:03:10.454 --> 00:03:11.669
See you there!
